      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="MM2-intro">iraṇṭāvatu ūralaruraittapāṭṭu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">The second song, in which gossip in the city is reported.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p type="edition"/>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="MM2">
          <l>nāva lōṅkiya māperun tīviṉuṭ</l>
          <l>kāvaṟ teyvatan tēvarkōṟ keṭutta</l>
          <l>tīvakac cānti ceytaru naṉṉāṇ</l>
          <l>maṇimē kalaiyoṭu mātavi vārāt</l>
          <l>taṇiyāt tuṉpan talaittalai mēlvarac</l>
          <l>cittirā patitāṉ cellaluṟ ṟiraṅkit</l>
          <l>tattari neṭuṅkaṭ taṉmaka ṭōḻi</l>
          <l>vayanta mālaiyai varukeṉak kūuyp</l>
          <l>payaṅkeḻu mānaka ralareṭut turaiyeṉa</l>
          <l> vayanta mālaiyu mātavi tuṟavik</l>
          <l>kayarntumey vāṭiya vaḻiviṉa ḷātaliṉ</l>
          <l>maṇimē kalaiyoṭu mātavi yirunta</l>
          <l>vaṇimalar maṇṭapat takavayiṟ celīi</l>
          <l>yāṭiya cāya lāyiḻai maṭantai</l>
          <l>vāṭiya mēṉi kaṇṭuḷam varuntip</l>
          <l>poṉṉē raṉaiyāy pukuntatu kēḷā</l>
          <l>yuṉṉō ṭivvū ruṟṟatoṉ ṟuṇṭukol</l>
          <l> vēttiyal potuviya leṉṟiru tiṟattuk</l>
          <l>kūttum pāṭṭun tūkkun tuṇivum</l>
          <l>paṇṇiyāḻk karaṇamum pāṭaip pāṭalun</l>
          <l>taṇṇumaik karuviyun tāḻtīṅ kuḻaluṅ</l>
          <l>kantukak karuttu maṭainūṟ ceytiyuñ</l>
          <l>cuntarac cuṇṇamun tūnī rāṭalum</l>
          <l>pāyaṟ paḷḷiyum paruvat toḻukkamuṅ</l>
          <l>kāyak karaṇamuṅ kaṇṇiya tuṇartaluṅ</l>
          <l>kaṭṭurai vakaiyuṅ karantuṟai kaṇakkum</l>
          <l>vaṭṭikaic ceytiyu malarāyntu toṭuttaluṅ</l>
          <l>kōlaṅ kōṭaluṅ kōvaiyiṉ kōppuṅ</l>
          <l>kālak kaṇitamuṅ kalaikaḷiṉ ṟuṇivu</l>
          <l>nāṭaka makaḷirkku naṉkaṉam vakutta</l>
          <l>vōviyac cennū lurainūṟ kiṭakkaiyuṅ</l>
          <l>kaṟṟut tuṟaipōkiya poṟṟoṭi naṅkai</l>
          <l> naṟṟavam purintatu nāṇuṭait teṉṟē</l>
          <l>yalakiṉ mūtū rāṉṟava rallatu</l>
          <l>palartoku puraikkum paṇpil vāymoḻi</l>
          <l>nayampā ṭillai nāṇuṭait teṉṟa</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">

          <l corresp="3"> On the auspicious days during which the Island Propitation [Festival] was
            performed—</l>
          <l corresp="2"> put on by the protective deity (Campu) for the king of the gods (Indra)</l>
          <l corresp="1"> on the great big island high with/famous for Jaumoon-plum trees
            (Camputtīvu),</l>
          <l corresp="4"> Mātavi and Maṇimēkalai did not come. </l>
          <l corresp="6"> As for Cittirāpati, she suffered affliction and wept.</l>
          <l corresp="5"> Unnabating grief overwhelmed [her] again and again.</l>
          <l corresp="7"> Red-streaks spread across her long eyes. </l>
          <l corresp="8"> She called Vayantamālai, her daughter's confidante, to come, </l>
          <l corresp="9"> and said, 'Tell [my daughter Mātavi] about the gossip [concerning hers and
            Maṇimēkalai's absence from the festival] in the great fertile city!' </l>
          <l corresp="10ab"> As for Vayantamālai— </l>
          <l corresp="13"> after entering the blossom-adorned pavillion </l>
          <l corresp="12"> where Mātavi was with Maṇimēkalai— </l>
          <l corresp="15"> she became sick at heart on seeing the faded body </l>
          <l corresp="14"> of that woman with choice jewels and a dancer's grace, </l>
          <l corresp="11"> because Mātavi had become a wreck, faded in body, dispirited, </l>
          <l corresp="10cd"> as a result of renunciation. </l>
          <l corresp="16"> [She] said [to her], 'O you who closely resemble Śrī! Listen to what has
            happened!</l>
          <l corresp="17"> Is there any [emnity] towards you that has arisen in the city? </l>
          <l corresp="32"> O gold-bangled lady, you who have studied and become expert in the branches
            of knowledge [which include]: </l>
          <l corresp="18-19">the dance of two types known as 'Royal Dancing' and 'Public Dancing',
            song,
            musical-modes and musical-timing/beat; </l>
          <l corresp="20">playing the tuneful lute, and singing melodies; </l>
          <l corresp="21">the Taṇṇumai drum instrument and the low, sweet flute; </l>
          <l corresp="22">the art of [playing] ball, and techniques in the art of cooking; </l>
          <l corresp="23">coloured powders, and swimming in pure water; </l>
          <l corresp="24">[the art of] the bedroom, and seasonal practices; </l>
          <l corresp="25">physical exercises/poses [64 in number], and understanding [others']
            intentions (i.e.
            mind-reading?); </l>
          <l corresp="26">types of figurative language, and the science of staying hidden; </l>
          <l corresp="27">techniques of the painting brush, and selecting and weaving blossoms [into
            garlands]; </l>
          <l corresp="28">applying [the arts of] beautification, and stringing [beads/flowers] in
            rows/on
            strings; </l>
          <l corresp="29">astrology and mastery of [all] the arts; </l>
          <l corresp="31">the contents of treatises on rhetoric/commentaries and of the refined
            treatises on
            painting </l>
          <l corresp="30">which are well assigned to dancing girls! </l>
<l corresp="34-35">Many crowds of people in the vast, ancient city—except for the decent ones—are repeating the embarassing truth: </l>
<l corresp="33">that [your] practice of good penance is a shameful thing. </l>
<l corresp="36" >This is undesirable—a shameful thing indeed,' said [Vayantamālai].     </l>

        </lg>
